-- Stocks in South Africa Rise for Second Day: Anglo American Old Mutual Move
-- B y   M i k e   C o h e n   a n d   G a r t h   T h e u n i s s e n
-- 2010-10-21T11:13:54Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-21/stocks-in-south-africa-rise-for-second-day-anglo-american-clicks-active.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  rose for a second day, advancing 264.55, or 0.9
percent, to 30,345.05 at 1:09 p.m. in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ) climbed for a second day,
advancing 4.21 rand, or 1.3 percent, to 317.71 rand. The
diversified mining company said third-quarter refined platinum
output expanded 11 percent from a year earlier as it sought to
take advantage of rising prices. Production rose to 697,000
ounces and unit  Anglo Platinum Ltd.  is poised to meet a full-
year estimate of 2.5 million ounces, London-based Anglo American
said today in a statement.  Anglo Platinum (AMS SJ, the world’s biggest producer of the
metal, increased for a second day, adding 5.31 rand, or 0.8
percent, to 6.99.98 rand.  MTN Group Ltd.  (MTN SJ), Africa’s biggest mobile-phone
company, rose for the first time in three days, climbing 1.35
rand, or 1.1 percent, to 122.90 rand. The company said it raised
about 2.8 billion rand ($404 million) selling shares under a
plan to encourage more investments by black South Africans in
accordance with local legislation.  Old Mutual  (OML SJ), Africa’s biggest insurer, fell 21
cents, or 1.4 percent, to 14.78 rand, a third day of declines.
The company may have to abandon plans to sell its controlling
stake in  Nedbank Group Ltd.  (NED SJ) as increased regulatory
scrutiny of financial companies forces potential buyers to focus
on improving their balance sheets at the expense of
acquisitions, Business Report said, citing  Tracy Brodziak , a
fund manager at Old Mutual Financial Services Fund.  Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, advanced 1.36 rand, or 0.4 percent, to 318.36
rand. Oil increased for a second day, adding as much as 1.1
percent to $82.70 a barrel.  To contact the reporters on this story:
